[1] Comment on Indonesia outbreak
Date: Mon 28 Nov 2022
From: T Jacob John <tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in> [edited]


Re: Poliomyelitis update (46): WPV1 ES, cVDPV2 AFP & ES, Indonesia community infection 20221127.8706935
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
It is not easy to wade through the reports and count the number of polio cases in the present [November 2022] outbreak. It appears that there were 3 paralysed children and 3 asymptomatically infected children also. Let me quote:

"The Health Ministry's spokesperson Muhammad Syahril reported that 3 children were confirmed positive for polio in Pidie District, Aceh. The children were suddenly paralyzed without showing any symptoms." These are most probably 3 polio paralysed children who had no prodromal symptoms, typical of polio.

Again: "In early November 2022, the Health Ministry declared an extraordinary occurrence (Kejadian Luar Biasa; KLB) of polio right after detecting one case in Pidie. Thus, an epidemiological search was launched in the region in 19 healthy children who had no contact with the initial case in order to assess whether or not virus transmission had occurred in the community." "From the results of examinations of 19 children, 3 children are found positive for the poliovirus," said Syahril in a written statement, [Thu 24 Nov 2022]. The examination was conducted by applying the targeted healthy stool sampling method as recommended by the WHO. However, according to WHO guidelines, the 3 children were not included in the case criteria because they did not suffer sudden paralysis."

The WHO "Poliovirus weekly update as of [Wed 23 Nov 2022]" reported the first case of polio, with VDPV-2, the onset of paralysis on [9 Oct 2022]. It will take more time for WHO to get formal reports from Health Ministry, and for verification in WHO laboratory network. However, the present problem is definitely due to VDPV-2. As the first case was caused by type 2 virus, we may assume that all 6 infections (3 paralysed, 3 asymptomatic) were infected by VDPV-2. What might its source be? After the tOPV to bOPV switch in 2016, children in Indonesia have no access to Sabin 2 vaccine virus. Is this imported from New York, London, Israel, or an Asian or African country with cVDPV-2? We must wait for a detailed genetic workup, which will certainly be conducted by WHO.

Although the immunisation coverage levels are very low, that was not the real risk factor for the appearance of VDPV-2. I wonder what vaccine will be used to prevent further cases. Hopefully, it will be IPV and not monovalent Sabin-2 or trivalent OPV containing types 1, 2, and 3. Giving Sabin 2 vaccine will seed more lineages of VDPV-2 in this community without any type 2 immunity.

Case-to-infection ratio of VDPV-2 cannot be any higher than that of wild type 2, which is 1/1000-2000. So, 3 polio cases indicate more than 3000 to 6000 infections. Even if I am wrong and the 3 refer to healthy children, the magnitude of virus circulation is huge, as 3 of 19 healthy children (16%) were infected.

--
T. Jacob John
Professor of Clinical Virology (retired)
Christian Medical College
Vellore,
India
<tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>

[ProMED would like to thank Prof. T Jacob John for his insightful comments. The media has been very difficult to interpret the actual number of infections vs AFP cases associated with infections. In section [2] below, the media report clarifies the count as 3 asymptomatic infections and 1 AFP-associated infection. But to play safe, we are asking for clarification from knowledgeable sources.

Prof T Jacob John rightfully raises the query of where did the VDPV2 come from as Indonesia uses only bivalent OPV (types 1 and 3) plus IPV (trivalent with types 1, 2, and 3). The answer will come when the results of genomic testing of the isolate(s) are available. This year [2022] there have been importations of VDPVs into countries that do not use OPV most notably the USA and the UK. The estimates of the number of infections with VDPV2 in Aceh is sobering.

For those who are interested in a recent review of VDPVs see https://polioeradication.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/20201118_cVDPV2_Global_Update_EN.pdf. - Mod.MPP]

