[2] Indonesian Media report
Date: Mon 28 Nov 2022
Source: Databoks [in Indonesian, machine trans., edited]
https://databoks.katadata.co.id/datapublish/2022/11/28/infeksi-polio-di-aceh-bertambah-ini-cakupan-vaksinasinya-5-tahun-terakhir


The Ministry of Health (Kemenkes) found that there were additional children infected with the polio virus in Pidie District, Aceh. These findings were obtained from the results of stool examination through Targeted Healthy Stools Sampling according to WHO recommendations, which was carried out on children under 5 years of age who lived around the location where the first polio case was found. "From the results of the examination of 19 children, it was found that 3 children were positive for the polio virus," said a spokesperson for the Ministry of Health, dr. Muhammad Syahril in his press release, [Thu 24 Nov 2022].

Even though they were infected, the 3 children who were positive for the polio virus were not included in the 'case' criteria, because they did not meet the criteria for having acute flaccid paralysis (AFC).

"Monitoring efforts are continuing, including screening efforts from house to house to ensure there are no additional cases of wilting paralysis that have not been reported," said dr. Syahril.

The first polio case was found in Pidie District in early November 2022. The Pidie District Government has designated this as an Extraordinary Polio Event (KLB) in their area.

"Polio is very dangerous for children because the impact is permanent for life, causes paralysis, and there is no cure. However, this condition can be easily prevented through complete polio immunization, both bOPV drip immunization, and IPV injection immunization," explained Dr. Syahril. "Therefore, we must protect the future of our children by giving them complete polio immunization," he continued.

Prior to the finding of this case, the coverage of polio immunization in Aceh Province in recent years tended to be low, as shown in the graph [source url has multiple graphs worth seeing - Mod.MPP]. During the 2017-2021 period, Aceh's polio immunization coverage was always below the national average. The occurrence of the COVID-19 pandemic is also one of the reasons for the decline in polio immunization coverage in the province in 2020-2021.

In addition to low immunization, the level of cleanliness of the Acehnese population is also considered to be still not good, so that it becomes a risk factor for virus transmission. "The presence of the polio virus in the faeces of the 3 children shows that the population still lacks clean and healthy behavior. The polio virus is transmitted through the gastrointestinal tract, while community defecation activities are still carried out in rivers, not in latrines, so there is virus circulation and the potential for transmission there" said Dr. Syahril.

[Byline: Viva Buddy Kusnandar]

